self-perceptions as they start school</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/G031770/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This research examined how twelve young children formed constructions of reading and perceptions of themselves as readers during the time of entry into the formal education system.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>As the study was concerned with understanding the children's perceptions, a range of age-appropriate games and activities were designed in order to access data directly from the children themselves.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>Following two cohorts of children, this longitudinal collective case study exposed the ways in which these children drew upon aspects of home reading experience, situated within contexts such as play, popular culture and digital texts, to shape their own understandings of reading. Yet the study revealed that many of these valuable constructions were at risk of disruption by the demands of the primary school curriculum. In particular, the dominant use of graded reading systems in school was seen to be largely constraining for most of the children in the study. In turn, many of the children were observed losing confidence in themselves as readers due to a lack of continuity between home and school discourses on reading. It is argued that educators must therefore build upon children's own constructions of reading to promote confidence and positive self-perceptions in a modern generation of young readers. &lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-08-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-09-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>63163</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>6F552D9E-04A8-48A6-87B8-920A2C0E9037</gtr:id><gtr:title>Children's perceptions of reading and the use of reading scheme texts</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Cambridge Journal of Education</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:a